31:00.267 --> 31:02.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN, PBS NEWSHOUR
ECONOMICS CORRESPONDENT:
Diana Alvord feels
lucky -- lucky that her

31:02.600 --> 31:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
daughter was born in September
without complication,
lucky that she came
home just days after she

31:09.500 --> 31:12.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was born, because four years
ago, Alvord's son was born,
prematurely, at just 24 weeks.

31:15.967 --> 31:18.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DIANA ALVORD: We
wondered for weeks and
weeks if he would live.

31:18.867 --> 31:23.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Alvord, who kept
vigil over him in the neonatal
intensive care unit for months,

31:25.867 --> 31:28.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also wondered how either of
them could have endured the
trial if she hadn't worked for

31:28.733 --> 31:31.667 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an accommodating non-profit
in Washington, D.C.

31:31.667 --> 31:36.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALVORD: I was given the
opportunity to just take a leave
of absence, and so, I was one

31:36.333 --> 31:41.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the few, probably, who
could return to their jobs
at the end of our ordeal.

31:41.067 --> 31:42.067 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But, I know.

31:42.067 --> 31:43.167 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: Unpaid, unpaid leave?

31:43.167 --> 31:45.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALVORD: Unpaid leave.

31:45.267 --> 31:47.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I know that there are
many people, that isn't
a choice that they have.

31:47.400 --> 31:49.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And most people have
to go back to work.

31:49.633 --> 31:53.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's really, an impossible
choice that families face.

31:53.533 --> 31:56.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Do I stay here and
hold my baby's hand?

31:56.067 --> 31:58.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Do I go to work and keep
the roof over our heads?

31:58.267 --> 32:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you put a price on
whether you stay or go?

32:02.100 --> 32:05.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SOLMAN: Many can't afford
to take unpaid leave.

32:05.333 --> 32:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yet, just thirteen percent
of American private sector
workers get any paid leave.

32:12.967 --> 32:15.067 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Alvord has seen the results.

32:15.067 --> 32:17.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALVORD: When I sat at his
bedside in the NICU, very,
very often, I was alone.

32:17.633 --> 32:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Very often, I would look around
the room and there would be 20
babies in all their separate

32:21.633 --> 32:25.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
isolettes, and there weren't 20
sets of caregivers around them.

32:25.167 --> 32:30.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: The U.S. is the only
industrialized country that
does not mandate any paid family

32:32.033 --> 32:35.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leave, giving the responsibility
to states and cities, like
the District of Columbia.

32:37.367 --> 32:40.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In D.C., supporters
lobbied for a paid leave
law for more than a year.

32:40.533 --> 32:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: This is an
urgent thing for me personally.

32:42.933 --> 32:46.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SOLMAN: But businesses and
the mayor balked at the cost.

32:46.167 --> 32:47.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE:
Councilmember Silverman.

32:47.167 --> 32:49.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: Yes.

32:49.300 --> 32:53.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Despite the backlash,
though, this week, D.C.'s city
council passed a scaled-back

32:53.933 --> 32:55.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
version of the bill.

32:55.200 --> 32:56.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE:
The measure passes.

32:56.200 --> 32:58.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(CHEERS)

32:58.200 --> 33:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: This means D.C. parents
who work in the private sector
can now take eight weeks

33:01.533 --> 33:06.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
off at up to 90 percent of
their pay, funded by a roughly
half-a-percent payroll tax on

33:08.567 --> 33:11.867 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
all non-government employers.

33:11.867 --> 33:16.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that, says Heather Boushey,
who studies work-life balance,
will be good for the local

33:17.433 --> 33:19.867 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
economy.

33:19.867 --> 33:22.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HEATHER BOUSHEY, WASHINGTON
CENTER FOR EQUITABLE
GROWTH: It boosts our
labor supply, especially

33:22.367 --> 33:25.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
among women and people who
have care responsibilities,
it increases job retention
for people, people

33:25.033 --> 33:29.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are more likely to keep their
job when they actually have
the tools to actually make it

33:29.100 --> 33:33.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
possible to balance all of
these competing challenges
in their daily life.

33:33.700 --> 33:37.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And all of that means
the economy is able to
tap into that talent.

33:37.333 --> 33:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: True, says Georgetown
University economist
Harry Holzer, but --

33:41.500 --> 33:46.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARRY HOLZER, GEORGETOWN
UNIVERSITY ECONOMIST:
There is a strong need
to balance the benefits

33:46.167 --> 33:51.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that workers and their families
get from paid family leave
with the costs on employers.

33:52.700 --> 33:56.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Holzer worries
the D.C. plan will
hobble local businesses.

33:56.367 --> 34:01.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HOLZER: They're providing 90
percent wage replacement up
to close to $1,000 a week.

34:03.267 --> 34:08.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're giving the worker almost
no incentive to limit the
amount of time they ask for.

34:09.933 --> 34:12.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Other states that have
done this provide 60
percent, maybe 70 percent.

34:12.733 --> 34:17.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: But what would
an employer do if it
was too expensive --
the cost was too high?

34:19.767 --> 34:24.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HOLZER: So, employers
can be quite ingenious
in terms of figuring
out ways to get the work

34:26.233 --> 34:28.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
done with fewer workers.

34:28.467 --> 34:33.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Another possibility is that
employers simply might move
across the river to Arlington,

34:34.067 --> 34:36.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Virginia.

34:36.033 --> 34:39.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Keep in mind that in the state
of Virginia, no one is required
to provide paid leave to

34:40.367 --> 34:41.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
employees.

34:41.900 --> 34:45.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: But D.C.
restaurant operator Greg
Casten now will be.

34:45.133 --> 34:47.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, will he skip town?

34:47.100 --> 34:50.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREG CASTEN, RESTAURANT
OPERATOR: You can't just pick
up a restaurant and move it over

34:50.167 --> 34:55.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the state line to avoid
the tax because restaurants
are, you know, the three
most important things:

34:56.300 --> 34:58.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
location, location, and,
of course, location.

34:58.300 --> 35:03.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Casten, who also co-owns
a seafood supply company,
complains the D.C. government

35:05.000 --> 35:09.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
already imposes a host of
costs on businesses, including
a recent minimum wage hike.

35:11.200 --> 35:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CASTEN: This just gives an idea
of how many different laws an
employer has to put up with.

35:16.533 --> 35:19.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm not saying any of
them on the face are bad.

35:19.600 --> 35:23.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
All I'm saying is,
there's a lot, a lot.

35:23.967 --> 35:28.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Casten insists most
employers will ultimately pass
on the cost to the employees

35:29.667 --> 35:30.667 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
themselves.

35:30.667 --> 35:32.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: But not every employer.

35:32.700 --> 35:37.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROGER HOROWITZ, EMPLOYER: For
us, it just really would be
extremely helpful as a way

35:43.433 --> 35:45.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to retain good employees.

35:45.500 --> 35:50.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Roger Horowitz
is the co-owner of
Pleasant Pops, purveyor
of popsicles and coffee.

35:52.767 --> 35:55.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
A major labor cost?

35:55.200 --> 35:57.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Employee turnover.

35:57.300 --> 36:00.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HOROWITZ: Between $2,000 and
$3,000 is how much it costs us
every time an employee leaves,

36:00.733 --> 36:03.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to train someone and
to fill their position.

36:03.800 --> 36:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: That's more than the
$2,000 Horowitz estimates the
new family leave tax will cost

36:09.267 --> 36:11.267 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
him.

36:11.267 --> 36:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HOROWITZ: We have an employee
who will in three months
and will not be able to, you

36:23.867 --> 36:28.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
know, have paid leave because
we don't have the financial
resources to make that happen

36:28.300 --> 36:30.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
right now.

36:30.000 --> 36:32.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: So, key for you
is that this functions
as an insurance policy?

36:32.633 --> 36:34.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HOROWITZ: Absolutely.

36:34.700 --> 36:38.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Being part of a larger pool
and working with all the other
small businesses and having

36:38.133 --> 36:41.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all that money be administered
by the city would be
very helpful for us.

36:41.833 --> 36:46.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: So Pleasant Pops pays
a small tax into the pool,
like all the other firms in

36:47.533 --> 36:49.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the city.

36:49.600 --> 36:53.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in return, it's insured,
so it can draw from the pool to
cover its costs if its employees

36:55.233 --> 36:57.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
need family leave.

36:57.633 --> 37:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But economist Holzer
worries other firms
will be discouraged from
employing low-income workers

37:04.367 --> 37:06.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if they think those
workers would be the most
likely to take paid leave.

37:06.933 --> 37:11.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HOLZER: They could simply cut
back on less educated young
women in the childbearing age

37:13.133 --> 37:15.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and just replace them
with other employees.

37:15.033 --> 37:20.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They would presumably try to
hire employees who would take

37:24.033 --> 37:26.267 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
less leave.

37:26.267 --> 37:31.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: But restaurant server
Shanae Bond illustrates just
how vulnerable workers are

37:34.300 --> 37:36.767 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as things currently stand.

37:36.767 --> 37:40.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
While pregnant with her daughter
Zane, Bond's employer axed her.

37:40.833 --> 37:45.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHANAE BOND: I believe I
was taken off the schedule
because I was pregnant.

37:45.400 --> 37:50.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that it was just
easier to accommodate other
servers wanting more hours.

37:52.400 --> 37:56.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Out of work, Bond has
gotten by only because her
father moved in and helps with

37:57.200 --> 37:58.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the bills.

37:58.400 --> 37:59.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DANTE CHURCH: She's
always held down a job.

37:59.667 --> 38:01.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She's always paid
her bills on time.

38:01.767 --> 38:06.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She never really had to ask
me or her mother for any help,
you know, until, you know, this

38:10.767 --> 38:15.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pregnancy and I know it was
hard for her to come to me.

38:15.333 --> 38:20.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: As for Diana
Alvord, that dangerously
premature baby is now this
fellow -- an imaginative

38:23.533 --> 38:25.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
four year old.

38:25.600 --> 38:29.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Alvord says the early days she
spent at her son's side were
critical to his development.

38:29.967 --> 38:33.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALVORD: Children's
outcomes are better if
they have skin-to-skin
contact, it's called

38:33.567 --> 38:38.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kangaroo care, you do it in
the NICU, and it's shown to
lower babies' stress hormones,

38:38.300 --> 38:42.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's shown to regulate
their heart rate, they
are able to regulate
their own body temperature

38:42.400 --> 38:44.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
sooner, their breathing
is more regular.

38:44.767 --> 38:48.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the economic argument part
of it comes in when you think
about the services and the

38:48.833 --> 38:53.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
care that the city
would otherwise provide
to these families and
these children later

38:53.167 --> 38:56.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on down the pipeline, rather
than investing right at the
first moment where you can make

38:56.733 --> 38:58.667 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a greater impact from day one.

38:58.667 --> 38:59.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What were you doing
with the Legos?

38:59.967 --> 39:02.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED KID:
Making (INAUDIBLE)

39:02.133 --> 39:04.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Oh, you made
another rocket ship.

39:04.900 --> 39:07.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And just look how
far her son has come.

39:07.233 --> 39:11.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALVORD: We were told that it
was in the single digits that
he would even come out of his

39:11.267 --> 39:16.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
birth surgery without incredible
complications like cerebral
palsy and all sorts of things.

39:17.133 --> 39:18.767 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, we were lucky, maybe.

39:18.767 --> 39:23.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Or, or maybe we did all
the things that there
are out there to do.

39:25.767 --> 39:29.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Things more
Washingtonians will now
be able to do, because
of paid family leave.

39:31.200 --> 39:35.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Washington, D.C.,
this is economics
correspondent Paul Solman.

39:37.067 --> 39:42.067 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
